segments.text: in the home of Bill Anderson in Corpus Christi.
Bill is the former director of planning in Corpus Christi.
And with that, I'd like to turn it over to Bill, and he will tell us about the history of planning in Corpus Christi.
I think the appropriate place to start is with the early promotion of the city.
And it was speculative.
It was done by a man by the name of Ropes that came from New York.
He had great visions that this would be the Venice of the United States, Venice of the Gulf Coast.
He spent a great deal of money digging a channel.
He built a big hotel.
He laid out a large subdivision that fixed the pattern of the streets
up to this time for a large portion of the city.
And in general, it was a very good plan.
During the Depression in 1908 or thereabout, it failed.
And for a long time, the city was only a resort center.
And in 1926,
A ship channel was built, and a harbor was located here, which assured the industrial development of the area.
And about the same time, oil was discovered and gas.
And shortly after, several industrial plants were built that were based largely on the availability of cheap
natural gas.
The next big event that took, well, during the Depression, the state planning officer, Major Wood, visited Corpus Christi and encouraged the city to, this was in 1935 or
thereabouts, encouraged the city to enact a zoning ordinance and a subdivision ordinance.
And to do so, encouraged the formation of an informal planning commission, citizens commission.
He loaned and gave some assistance to the citizens commission.
And they formulated a zoning ordinance.
Now, this zoning ordinance was a good thing, but it was not based on scientific analysis of the problems or land use.
There was no comprehensive plan.
There was no comprehensive plan.
And there was no comprehensive study of land use.
These citizens, who were very highly respected citizens on the Planning Commission and knew the city pretty well at that time, used their best judgment in laying out the zoning districts.
Shortly after, they enacted a subdivision ordinance.
Along about this time, the National Resources Planning Board
offered the city a study called a sketch plan.
And I don't know exactly how it got started, but there were several architects, most of them graduates of Texas A&M.
One of the leaders was Richard Colley.
How does he spell that name?
C-O-L-L-E-Y.
a very capable and competent architect.
And there were some other architects involved.
And Sam Zisman evidently was an advisor to this group.
They got together and had some citizens' committees.
And they made some very rough sketches that kind of designated areas.
suitable for various purposes, sketchy type drawings.
Nothing really came of this, but it did serve to stimulate some interest among the citizens of the city.
I don't believe many of the top leaders got involved.
But there were quite a few citizens that were in it.
League of Women Voters, and Garden Club people, and architects, and other groups.
Sam Zussman was assigned here out of the National?
I think he was.
I think he was signed here.
And Bob Mitchell from the National Resources Board, I think, was here one time.
But I think Zisman was kind of the guidance to the local people.
And nothing came, really, of this sketch plan.
Is that the Robert Mitchell that taught at the University of Pennsylvania?
Yeah.
I studied him.
He was a fraternity brother of mine at University of Illinois Alpha Rho Chi.
Really?
I studied under him at Penn.
Yeah, I was now for up there in Illinois.
Well, as I said, nothing really came specific from this sketch plan, except it served a good educational media, which I think was one of the purposes that it had.
Well, as I understand it, this was one of the first
federal attempts at what might be called a demonstration, a national demonstration.
Yeah, this was selected as one of the cities for the demonstration.
There weren't many.
No, there were only five or six, I think.
I believe so, during the Depression era.
Yeah, there were only five or six of them.
And this was one of them.
And I think it was very worth, I think it was worthwhile.
Now, the next important.
It was the only one in Texas.
Yeah.
The only one in Texas.
I think the next, well, along about 19, oh, long about this time, 38 or 39, the government decided to establish a naval air training station here in Corpus Christi.
And they bought a large tract of land south of the city and built a naval training station, a naval air training station.
And it eventually became one of the largest ones in the country, or one of the largest in the world.
They had flying boats, and they had
a propeller aircraft, and they had a lot of auxiliary fields.
Also, at Ward Island, which is a little isolated tract of land south of the city, they had a radar training station, which was a super secret installation.
People in the town didn't really know what it was, but there were a lot of people assigned here, and there was a lot of
A lot of civilian employees and a lot of naval employees here.
And the city grew.
But there was very poor housing, and they couldn't.
They had to resort to the old tourist courts for the people that accompanied the military and civilians.
And it resulted in a lot of slummy property, particularly on Corpus Christi Beach.
Right at the end of the war, then, a political event took place, which was very significant.
Prior to this time, the city had a commission form of government, and it was a very poor one.
Inherited from Galveston, I have no doubt.
Well, I don't know how long they had it, but they had it for some time, and it was...
a very unwholesome thing, particularly with the high proportion of Mexican-Americans we had.
The commissioners used their position to control the votes of the Mexican-Americans.
And the Mexican-Americans at that time were a very uneducated group.
They were primarily cotton pickers.
They lived in a section of the city that was a very slum section west of the city, where a good deal of it was outside the city.
No sewers, no water, no drainage.
It was just a horrible situation.
We had a Negro section that was pretty well segregated over on the north side.
And this contained a great deal of substandard housing.
and segregated schools.
At this time, a group of citizens, realizing that Corpus Christi was on the go and would continue to grow because of the oil activity and increasing industrial activity that was caused by the
ship channel, that this city was destined to grow and grow fast.
The leading citizens got together.
They were heads of the industries, and they were all top-notch people.
And they represented what later became called the power structure.
They established the city manager form of government in the city through the leadership of this group.
Then they
got some of these people to serve on the city council, one of which was Robert Wilson, the brother of Charles E. Wilson, who was president of General Motors.
And people of that caliber were on the city council, bankers.
Also, one of the leading oil men in the city was made president of the Chamber of Commerce, Guy Warren.
And together, they conceived the idea of a citizen's group called the Area Development Committee.
And on this Area Development Committee, they had some 30 people, 25 people, that were all leaders, that were top owners of the businesses,
the biggest businesses.
They were presidents of the banks, managers of the industries, top oil men that owned their companies.
And there was around 25 of them.
And they conceived this idea of a citizens committee
to guide the growth and development of the city.
They realized that they were... About what year was that?
This was in about 1945.
Right after the war.
Right after the war.
About 1945.
And 46.
Well, they realized that...
They were businessmen, and they didn't know anything about the mechanics of government and the details of government.
And they would need some help.
So they formed a second committee called a coordination committee.
And on that committee, they had all the political leaders, like the county judge, the mayor, the superintendent of schools,
and the district engineer of the highway department, and others, including the director of the Chamber of Commerce, or the executive director.
And they had the president of the Citizens Council, the Nueces Navigation District, Water Supply District, and all of the political leaders.
Well, these were the ones that were asked to
do something about the guiding of the growth of the city.
In turn, this group got together and decided that they needed some technical assistance.
So they then appointed what was known as a subcommittee.
And on this subcommittee, they had one, two, three, four, five engineers.
two lawyers and the Secretary of the Chamber of Commerce.
They gave this group an assignment.
They said, now here's what we want to do, now you tell us how to do it.
So this group got together and they wrote to ASPO, American Institute of Planners, American Society of Civil Engineers,
and a number of other groups, United States Chamber of Commerce, and told them what we wanted to do and asked them to tell us who could do it and tell us some names, give us some names of people.
So we got all these names, and we got suggestions of how to go about it.
So the next thing was to interview these people.
So we had 14 of the top firms in the United States.
come to Corpus Christi and look the situation over and tell us how they would approach the problem or what they thought ought to be in a plan.
Was there any money put up for this effort?
Well, I'll get to that.
I think most of the consultants came in here at their own expense.
Up to this time, there was very little money in it.
Now, this committee reported back through channels what we needed and what suggested a program.
And we told them it was going to cost them some money.
Now, this committee, the Area Development Committee, decided to assess their members.
And they assessed their members at the rate, each time, about $1,000 apiece.
And they could afford it because they were the power structure and leading citizens.
And after interviewing all these people, the firm that stood out the most was the firm of Harlan Bartholomew and Associates.
They seemed to have the most practical approach and the one that seemed to satisfy the members of the committee the most.
had placed me in an awkward position because prior to coming to Corpus Christi, I had been employed by that firm.
I asked to be declared ineligible to participate because of my connection.
But the rest of the committee went on, and they did select the Bartholomew firm.
Well, Bill, when did you get to Corpus Christi?
I came in 1946 with the reform government.
Now, I was the second city planner.
They had a city council prior to Robert Wilson that was not acceptable, and they were recalled.
But they had employed a building inspector
Austin as their planner.
And he was only here for about nine months.
And with the recall movement.
You don't remember his name.
Yeah, I do.
I'll think of it in a minute.
OK.
With the recall movement, he didn't want to stay on with the city government.
He thought that if the city government was that bad, he didn't want to be on it, on the staff.
So he resigned.
So then when the new city council, Robert Wilson, came in, they went about contacting ASPO and American Society of Civil Engineers and other people.
United States Chamber of Commerce for suggestions for a planner.
I was one of three that was interviewed.
They paid my expenses down here from New Jersey.
You were living in New Jersey then?
I was living in Newark working on a comprehensive plan with
for the city of Newark was Bartholomew.
Ah, yes.
That's where he started his practice, was in Newark.
Yeah, and I have a copy of their first comprehensive plan there.
Ah.
Well.
Do you know the other two that were interviewed?
Or does it matter?
One guy, he went with the National Resources Planning Board.
Pretty good boy.
Uh-huh.
The other one I don't remember.
Matter of fact, they had a little job selling me to come because I had gotten on a plane with a naval officer that had apparently didn't like Corpus Christi and gave me a pretty good unselling.
But before the day was over,
of my interview, they convinced me that there was a great challenge here and that they wanted me.
They paid my expenses down here.
One of the department store owners brought me down.
I didn't decide for a week, but they called me every day.
And then I finally decided to come
got permission to be released by Bartholomew.
And this is the reason that I declared myself disqualified to participate in the selection of a firm because I didn't want my association to affect it.
Well, Bartholomew started out on the plans.
It was about a $100,000 contract.
Big money in those days.
And that was a pretty good sized contract for it.
But considering what was involved in it, I don't think it was too much.
Because Bartholomew went outside of his firm and employed a number of other consultants.
One of the big problems, we had three major problems.
One was a water supply.
One was the problem of the constricting bridge that we had at the entrance to the channel.
It restricted the flow of marine traffic.
It was a bottleneck for
for both railroad and vehicular traffic.
So Bartholomew went outside of his firm and got the most qualified engineers in each of these fields that he could find.
He got W.W. Horner, who was then president of the American Society of Civil Engineers, as his engineer advisor on the water supply and the airport.
He got Sverdrup and Parcell, one of the top bridge engineers in the United States, and railroad engineers on the problem of the bridge.
No, Sverdrup, that's S-V-E-R-D-R-U-P?
Yes, Sverdrup and Parcell.
And Parcell.
Yeah, you can see their ad in the paper.
Well, Bartholomew went about a very thorough study.
about three years to complete it.
He started in 1950 and finished it in 1953.
Now his technique, of course, is to take each subject and write a very thorough treatise on it, as much as time and funds would permit.
And he got out separate reports on each subject.
and including in these subjects were economic background, population, land use, housing, streets and highways, transportation, transit,
parking, schools and parks, public buildings, water supply, storm drainage, public works, and administration.
Now, each of these subjects had a separate and pretty good sized report, which were circulated to an extensive citizens committee that included several hundred citizens
that were appointed by the Area Development Committee.
And they were, they were presumably the leading citizens on the various subjects that they were interested in, that knew and had some knowledge.
So immediately,
A big citizen support was engendered.
And all these were leaders, too.
So each one of these reports was very thoroughly examined, several of them rewritten.
And finally, they were
in such a shape that all the citizens were satisfied.
They were then submitted to the Area Development Committee, which eventually approved them.
And then they authorized the publication of the summary, which is this volume here, which was called the Comprehensive Plan.
Now, of course, anybody can make a plan.
Any planner can make a plan.
He can arrange the streets and the parks in good order.
But it's quite another thing to also plan to implement it and figure out how to pay for it and keep it within scale, the ability of the community to pay for it.
And this was part of the assignment.
And one of the reasons that the plan was very successful was this phase of it.
They not only suggested what they needed, but how they could pay for it.
For instance, when the bridge was built, and we call it the Railroad Relocation Project, or the
The elimination of the Bascule Bridge bottleneck is what was known locally, and we dubbed it the Bascule Bottleneck Project.
We got involved there with the federal government through the Truman Hobbs Act.
It took some research to find out that there was funds available for the relocation of a bridge due to the needs of navigation.
We got the Highway Department involved for building the high bridge.
And so altogether, we had the federal government primarily on the Truman Hobbs and the relocation of the ship channel.
That's a relocation of the bridge.
We had the Highway Department on the high bridge and the connections to it.
which eventually expanded into a freeway system for the city.
We had the city and the county and the navigation district involved, each with a share in the cost of it.
And it was divided according to their legal authority to do certain phases of this.
So we had a very complicated formula on the financing of it.
But we knew before we started we could finance it.
We also had four railroads that were competing railroads.
And they weren't speaking to each other.
And we had to get their total cooperation in order to make this work.
I'm going back now to one other thing.
In this area development committee,
We had the president of the Chamber of Commerce I mentioned was Guy Warren.
And he had the good sense to appoint the president of the power company.
